PART 1.

The appropriate analysis for exploring the relationships between climate change perspectives, information exposure, education attainment, poverty levels and coastline on the proportion of people who believe that global warming is happening is to use a Multiple Linear Regression because it makes logical sense that an increase in information, education, and immediate impact would be linearly related to opinion on the topic of global warming.

It is interesting yet expected that the proportion of people who think global warming is happening is 2.5% greater among people who live in states with coastline when compared to those living in states without coastline.

Another interesting and surprising coefficient is that the proportion of respondents whi think global warming is happening is only 0.36% greater among people who recieved a Bachelors degree than among those who do not have a Bachelors degree.

The model presented does not present significant concerns for homoscedasticity and the residual variance seems normal. The assumption of normality presents a slight cause for concern, as the upper and lower tail of the residuals does not follow a pattern of normal distribution, however the majority of the residuals do appear to be normally distributed.

PART 2.

In order to determine if there is a significant effect of race on individual’s perception of campus respect at UCSB, a chi-square test is used to test if proportions of respondents in different groups are significantly different.

Based on results from the UCSB Campus Climate Survey (2014), race identity of respondents had a significant effect on the perception of campus climate [(\(\chi^2\)(18) = 1490, p < 0.001.]

TABLE CAPTION
Race Very Respectful Respectful Disrespectful Very Disrespectful
African American/African/Black 1950 4158 562 121
American Indian/Alaskan Native 1882 3864 271 78
Asian/Asian American 2132 4329 424 57
Hispanic/Latino 1979 4324 553 98
Middle Eastern/South Asian/North African 1870 4135 507 109
Pacific Islander 1959 4126 235 46
White 3623 3654 108 41

The results show that the majority of each race group would classifiy the campus environment at UCSB as respectful or very respectful, however there were larger proportions of respodents that felt the campus environment was either disrespectful or very disrespectful within the African American, Hispanic and Middle Eastern groups. Additionally, for all race groups except White, more a larger portion of respondents felt the campus was respectful compared to very respectful, while responses within White students were nearly equal for both respectful and very respectful.

PART 4.


Based on the data exploration above, the data does not seem to be normally distributed, and observations for one group (carrots) are below 30 so the Central Limit Theorem does not apply. Because of this, I will use a Mann Whitney U test to check for significant difference in median pesticide concentration between carrots and strawberries.

Based on the data of pesticide residues from the California Department of Pesticide Regulation, there is a significant difference in median pesticide quantity detected between carrots and strawberries [W = 508.5, p < 0.001] and the effect size is large (cliff’s delta = 0.695).

#a. Any code used to wrangle the data and prepare your final graph.

# create a new dataframe with a column that calculates pesticide per square mile
# arrange from highest to lowest pesticide per square mile
# keep only the top 10
pesticide_df <- ca_county_pesticides %>% 
  mutate(pounds_per_mile = pounds_active/area) %>% 
  arrange(-pounds_per_mile) %>% 
  head(10)

# keep current levels so the graph doesnt reorder county alphabetically but order is based on highest to lowest pesticide per square mile 

pesticide_factor <- pesticide_df %>% 
  mutate(county = factor(county, levels = county))
